install.packages("tidyverse")
install.packages("ggplot2")
install.packages("conflicted")
install.packages("lubridate")

Explore IoT Dataset

# Since ORYZA takes daily values we get group by day and get the mean
# values of each parameter
iot_daily <- iot_data %>%
  # 1) Extract the calendar day from your POSIXct
  mutate(day = as.Date(date)) %>%
  # 2) Group by that day
  group_by(day) %>%
  # 3) Average every numeric column except the original date
  summarise(
    min_temp = min(temperature, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_temp = max(temperature, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_h = mean(humidity, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_n = mean(N, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_p = mean(P, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_k = mean(K, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Inspect

# Plot Temperature and Humidity
ggplot(iot_daily, aes(x = day)) +
  # ribbon for temperature
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = min_temp,
                  ymax = max_temp),
              fill  = "firebrick",
              alpha = 0.5) +
  # line for humidity, but well rescale it to sit on the same primary axis
  geom_line(aes(y = mean_h * (max(iot_daily$max_temp)/100)),
            color = "steelblue",
            size  = 1) +
  
  # primary axis is temperature
  scale_y_continuous(
    name     = "Temperature (C)",
    # mirror secondary axis by undoing the scale factor
    sec.axis = sec_axis(~ . * (100 / max(iot_daily$max_temp)),
                        name = "Humidity (%)")
  ) +
  
  labs(
    x     = "Date",
    title = "Daily MinMax Temperature & Mean Humidity"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x     = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "none"
  )

# 1) Pivot to long form
daily_long <- iot_daily %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols      = c(mean_n, mean_p, mean_k),
    names_to  = "Nutrient",
    values_to = "Concentration"
  )

# 2) Overlayed line plot
ggplot(daily_long, aes(x = day, y = Concentration, color = Nutrient)) +
  geom_line(size = 0.8) +
  scale_x_date(
    date_labels = "%b %Y",    # e.g. "Nov 2023"
    date_breaks = "1 month"
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Daily Mean N, P & K Over Time",
    x     = "Date",
    y     = "Mean Concentration",
    color = "Nutrient"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x     = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "bottom"
  )

The red ribbon is the minimum and max temperature within the day and the blue line is the humidity.

Solar radiation and rain can be gathered from other IoT sensors but as of the current dataset we have, we can use the dataset to construct the same table to get the max-min temperature and humidity

Explore res dataset

This dataset contains the daily output of the model during the simulation. TIME = Day number CROPSTA = growth status (1 for sowing, 2 for seed bed, 3 for transplanting, 4 for main field) TMIN = Daily min temperature TMAX = Daily max temperature SON = Total soil organic nitrogen WRR14 = Grain yield 14% of moisture

The model has much more variables which provide information about the quality of yield and performance of the crop during the season.
